courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of the course, students should be able to

(1) understand basic concepts in statistics;
(2) use various statistical methods and techniques to summarise, present and analyse data;
(3) read statistical reports and recognise when the quantitative information being presented is accurate or misleading; and

(4) use computer software to analyse data and draw conclusions.

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to

(1) learn the basic concepts in statistics;
(2) organise and display graphical and numerical data summaries and draw conclusions from them;
(3) demonstrate an understanding of the basic principles of probability and apply some of the basic probability distributions to real-life examples;
(4) apply the central limit theorem;
(5) perform hypothesis testing on one- and two-sample problems; and

(6) perform simple statistical analysis using MS Excel.

1) Familiar with Data Science Toolbox: GitHub; VS-code; Python: numpy, pandas, seaborn, sklearn; Colab; Jupyter notebook; Markdown;
2) Analyze continuous and categorical data using statistics, Python programming based on Colab and software as appropriate;
3) Ability in using advanced Python tools to describe, summarize, and visualize dataset;
4) Understand and implement good coding practices, including statistical inference on A/B test, and statistical learning/prediction based on tabular data.

courses.course_syllabus:
1) Introduction to GitHub: version control; git clone, commit, push, REPO management;
2) Basic coding in Python based on Colab: basic syntax, data type, and loop in Python;
3) Functions and Classes in Python: numpy, pandas, sklearn, statmodels;
4) Introduction to Markdown and Jupyter Notebook: share your work;
5) Getting data: conversions, Kaggle, and web scraping;
6) Data visualizations based on seaborn;
7) Introduction to A/B test;
8) Case study: Mobile Games A/B Test with Cookie Cats;
9) Top-3 presentations;
10) Introduction to Machine Learning Prediction;
11) Case study: Titanic - Machine Learning from Disaster;
12) Advance lecture: Deep learning and its application;
13) Guest lecture: The role of big data analytics in industry.

