courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of the course, students should be able to
(1) apply intermediate mathematical and statistical methodologies to practical problems;
(2) apply critical and analytical skills to conduct primitive research;
(3) implement intermediate data analysis and statistical computing algorithms;
(4) communicate data analysis findings with teammates and general audiences.

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to

(1) understand the typical designs of life science studies;
(2) use descriptive statistics to explore data;
(3) choose appropriate statistical tests (e.g., Z-test, t-test, F-test, chi-square test and selected nonparametric tests), implement them and interpret their results;
(4) apply and interpret methods for comparison, correlation and regression analyses; and

(5) calculate statistical power and determine sample size for commonly used statistical tests.

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to

(1) use various statistical methods and techniques to summarize and present high-dimensional data;
(2) build predictive models for complex data sets;
(3) master the concepts of regularization, model selection, model averaging and ensemble learning; and

(4) write R code and use R packages to solve real-world problems.

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to
(1) extend standard univariate techniques to their multivariate counterparts;
(2) describe and interpret correlation structures;
(3) perform and interpret multivariate techniques including analysis of means, profile analysis, principal component analysis, factor analysis and partial correlation analysis; and
(4) analyze real data by appropriate techniques and software.

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to
(1) analyse and interpret categorical data accurately;
(2) understand the applicability of different techniques of analysing categorical data;
(3) appreciate the relationships between different methods for analysing categorical data; and
(4) model categorical data.

Upon finishing the course, students are expected to
(1) distinguish the difference between frequentist and Bayesian methods, and identify their pros and cons;
(2) derive posterior distributions from commonly-used prior and sampling distributions;
(3) select appropriate Bayesian tools for different statistical tasks, e.g., estimation, testing, model selection, prediction, etc.;
(4) perform Markov chain Monte Carlo in R; and
(5) build Bayesian models for solving real problems and perform proper statistical analysis.

After taking this course, the students are expected:
1) To understand the fundamental statistical concepts and principles behind different multilayer neural networks such as CNN, GAN and RNN;
2) To master the mechanisms and probability theory behind common reinforcement learning models;
3) To have the critical mind on deciding which deep learning tools could be applied to a concrete real dataset;
4) To formulate deep learning framework for modeling problems arisen in business, quantitative finance and risk management science.

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to

(1) understand and get a taste of the real industrial business;

(2) learn communication skills among collaborators;

(3) learn practical quantitative skills for statistics and data science;

(4) conduct research on statistics and data science problems; and

(5) learn presentation skills.

